What you are trying to achieve isn&#39;t just &quot;sorting&quot; or &quot;shuffling&quot;, it&#39;s ***permutation***, i.e. generating every possible ordering of a sequence. Permutation has factorial complexity, i.e. the number of possibilities for *n* items is `n!`, not `2^n - 1`. For example, for 5 items, there are 120 possibilities `5! = 5*4*3*2*1 = 120`.

There is a fairly basic way of writing a recursive program that performs permutation. Basically, take the first element of the list; swap it with each element of the rest of the list; and with each swap, generate the permutation of the rest of the list. For a clearer explanation, you can just look up how to permute a list using recursion.

This is how you would implement it in Java:


&lt;!-- language: java --&gt;
    
    import java.util.Scanner;
    import java.util.Set;
    import java.util.LinkedHashSet;
    
    public class Permutation {
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Scanner scan = new Scanner(System.in);
            System.out.print(&quot;Type in up to 7 letters (no spaces): &quot;);
            String input = scan.nextLine().trim();
            if (input.length() &gt; 7) {
                input = input.substring(0, 7);
            }
            Set&lt;String&gt; possibilities = permutation(input);
            for (String s : possibilities) {
                System.out.println(s);
            }
        }
    
        public static Set&lt;String&gt; permutation(String input) {
            // LinkedHashSet preserves the order in which we generate values
            // If you want the values sorted instead, use TreeSet
            Set&lt;String&gt; output = new LinkedHashSet&lt;&gt;();
            perm(input.toCharArray(), 0, output);
            return output;
        }
    
        public static void perm(char[] input, int start, Set&lt;String&gt; output) {
            if (start + 1 &gt;= input.length) {
                // we&#39;ve reached the end of the input, so record the current state
                output.add(String.valueOf(input));
                return;
            }
            // for first recursion, don&#39;t swap anything
            perm(input, start + 1, output);
            for (int i = start + 1; i &lt; input.length; i++) {
                char a = input[start];
                char b = input[i];
                // for each successive recursion, swap the next character
                input[start] = b;
                input[i] = a;
                // run permutation for the rest of the list
                perm(input, start + 1, output);
                // and swap back when it&#39;s done
                input[start] = a;
                input[i] = b;
            }
        }
    }

