Assuming that there would be only lower case English letters in the given `String` the most performant way would be to add `+1` to every character, and use either `if`-statement checking whethe the initial character was `z` or use the [modulo operator](https://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=2ahUKEwiRx7yn0N_5AhUKl4sKHXxSCcwQFnoECAUQAQ&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fen.wikipedia.org%2Fwiki%2FModulo_operation&amp;usg=AOvVaw3HGWtuIdoNdD7Ahy948lWx) `%` as *@sp00m* has pointed out in the [comment](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/73473612/what-is-the-best-way-to-replace-a-letter-with-the-letter-following-it-in-the-alp/73474568#comment129749951_73473612).

Performing a search in the alphabetic string (*option 1* in your list) is **redundant**, as well extracting array `char[]` from the given string (*option 3*).

*Checking the edge case:*

    public static String shiftLetters(String str) {
        
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; str.length(); i++) {
            char next = str.charAt(i);
            if (next == &#39;z&#39;) result.append(&#39;a&#39;);   // checking the edge case
            else result.append((char) (next + 1));
        }
        
        return result.toString();
    }

*Applying modulo operator:*

    public static String shiftLetters(String str) {
        
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; str.length(); i++) {
            char next = (char) ((str.charAt(i) - &#39;a&#39; + 1) % 26 + &#39;a&#39;);
            result.append(next);
        }
        
        return result.toString();
    }

`main()`

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(shiftLetters(&quot;abc&quot;));
        System.out.println(shiftLetters(&quot;wxyz&quot;));
    }

*Output:*
```
bcd   // &quot;abc&quot;
xyza  // &quot;wxyz&quot;
```

